Data preparation

I am only interested to know more about my top 3 favorite Lana Del Rey albums. Thus, I decided to only select those three for my study. These include: âBorn To Die - The Paradise Editionâ, âUltraviolence (Deluxe)â and âHoneymoon.â

#Remove records with the same track names
data <- data |> distinct(track_name, .keep_all = TRUE) 
data <- data |> filter(!grepl("pattern_to_exclude", track_name))
data$album_name <- as.character(data$album_name)

Album analysis (valence and energy)

# Change album_name from character to factor before plotting 
data$album_name <- as.factor(data$album_name)

# Filter data for the specific albums you want
selected_albums <- c("Born To Die - The Paradise Edition", "Ultraviolence (Deluxe)", "Honeymoon")
filtered_data <- data[data$album_name %in% selected_albums, ]

# Plot a boxplot
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(filtered_data, aes(x = album_name, y = valence)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(x = "Album name", y = "Valence")

For valence level, the album Honeymoon has the lowest median. Was Lana Del Rey sad when writing songs for the album Honeymoon?

Letâs see if Honeymoon also has the lowest energy level.

# Filter data for the specific albums you want
selected_albums <- c("Born To Die - The Paradise Edition", "Ultraviolence (Deluxe)", "Honeymoon")
filtered_data <- data[data$album_name %in% selected_albums, ]

# Plot histogram and density for the selected albums
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(filtered_data, aes(x = tempo)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), fill = "purple", color = "black", binwidth = 3) +
  geom_density(fill = "#FF6666", alpha = 0.5) +
  facet_grid(album_name ~ .) +
  labs(title = "Relation of the tempo to density of data's songs per album", x = "Tempo (BPM)", y = "Density")

These results did not come as a surprise to me. This is the case as the album âBorn To Die - The Paradise Editionâ is mostly known for its poetic and emotive qualities rather than the concentration of musical elements.

To have a deeper overview of Lana Del Reyâs music, letâs take a look at the songs with the least valence level from my favorite albums of Lana Del Rey.

filtered_data |> slice_min(valence, n=3) |> dplyr::select(track_name, album_name, album_release_year, valence) |> knitr::kable(digits = 2)

Funnily enough, different results were found when looking at energy levels. Ultraviolence is apparently the least energetic song out of all three of my top favorite Lana Del Rey albums.

Now, letâs explore the relationship between Loudness and Energy with regards to all songs from my top 3 Lana Del Rey albums.

ggplot(filtered_data, aes(x = loudness, y = energy,))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method= "lm", alpha = 0.1, fill= "blue")+
  labs(title="Relationship between Loudness and Energy of filtered_data's songs", x="Loudness", y="Energy")

From these results, we can say that the louder the song gets, the more eneregetic it is.

Now, I am interested to check where my 3 favorite songs of my top 3 Lana Del Rey albums stand relatively to the rest of the songs from those three albums regarding energy and valence.

subgroup <- data |> filter(track_name %in% c("Dark Paradise","Ultraviolence","High By The Beach"))
ggplot(filtered_data, aes(x = valence, y = energy, color = album_name))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0.5, color="grey")+
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0.5, color="grey")+
  geom_text(data=subgroup, aes(label=track_name))

We can see now that High By The Beach, for example is one of the highest energetic songs from the album it is from. Nevetheless, it remains a fairly calm song, like the rest of the album, as it has a score of 0.50 out of 1 in energy levels.

Data analysis (Speechiness)

Lana Del Rey is one of my favorite artists because I find her songwriting evocative and distinct. My favorite album is âBorn To Die - The Paradise Editionâ for that precise reason. In this way, letâs observe if the level of speechiness is the highest for that album!

# Assuming album_name is already a factor in your data
data$album_name <- as.factor(data$album_name)

# Filter data for the specific albums you want
selected_albums <- c("Born To Die - The Paradise Edition", "Ultraviolence (Deluxe)", "Honeymoon")
filtered_data <- data[data$album_name %in% selected_albums, ]

# Plot bar plot with error bars for mean speechiness
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(filtered_data, aes(x = album_name, y = speechiness)) +
  stat_summary(fun.y = mean, geom = "bar", position = "dodge", fill = "darkblue") +
  stat_summary(fun.data = mean_cl_normal, geom = "errorbar", position = "dodge", width = 0.2, color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Mean Speechiness for Selected Albums", x = "Album Name", y = "Speechiness")

âBorn To Die - The Paradise Editionâ is indeed the album with the highest speechiness level.

All in all, from the albums I analysed, my favorite album, âBorn To Die - The Paradise Editionâ has the highest valence, energy, speechiness levels and the lowest density level.
